                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The Supreme Court found in 1916 in the case Brushaber v. Union Pacific R.R. Co.; 240 U.S. 1, that the 16th Amendment didn't extend the taxing powers of Congress. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Uhg...this is the kind of stuff that gets bandied about by people who claim its possible to 'opt out' of the system.<br /><br />Go read the case.  The Court found the income tax was legal and that Union Pacific had to pay income taxes.<br /><br />The justice who wrote the opinion was attempting to write the holding in a way that would permit the federal government to tax 'income', but not 'capital'. He did a bad job writing the thing, because the distinction the judge believed was 'obvious' is actually arbitrary and subject to accounting slights-of-hand.  And subsequent case history has pretty much accepted that and ignored the opinion.<br /><br />In constitutional law classes the case is used as example of 1) an incomprehensible opinion; 2) A case where judges intentionally twist the entire legislative history of a law while interpreting it; and 3) a case that gets ignored by every subsequent court within a few years of its decision.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">In 1991, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals held that if someone claims they are not subject to the federal income tax, then the burden to prove the contrary is on the IRS.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I assume you mean the 'Cheek' case.  Again, go read the damn case.  You are 99.9% wrong.<br /><br />The court held that if you can show you have a 'good faith' misunderstanding of the tax code, the government cannot toss you into prison for tax evasion. Thats the 0.1% where you are right. <br /><br />The government argued that it should be able to lock up a taxpayer for several years if his intrepretation of the tax code was not 'reasonable'.  But that would have meant the IRS could lock you up if you ever had a question on your taxes and failed to consult a tax expert about it.  Of course the Supreme Court rejected that argument.  Its ridiculous (as well as a fine example of the way the Justice Department lawyers think).<br /><br />And by the way, the Supreme Court then specifically found that Cheek DID NOT HAVE A GOOD FAITH ARGUMENT!  They sent Cheek to prison for tax evasion.<br /><br />And forget about the criminal law for a second.  The government can make you pay back taxes and CIVIL PENALTIES, which usually amount to a big multiple of the unpaid taxes, just by proving you intentionally failed to pay, whatever your reason.  (Another free piece of advice: Even DEATH is not a valid excuse for failing to file and pay taxes).  The Cheek opinion points this out as a reason for requiring the government prove more before obtaining a criminal conviction.<br /><br />By all means, rely on Cheek.  Justice Department geeks will cite the case in the arguments that get the doors on you cell double-locked at the end of your appeal. <br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />By wording your above post as "free advice from a one-time attorney," how would that be viewed in an actual court of law? Im not trying to imply anything here, just curious as to the liability implications of it all.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I gave you one free piece of advice, now you want more?  Forget it.  Go hire a malpractice attorney.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">In any event, I hate to sink to your level (insults rather than valid arguments),<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Now this is just sad and whiny. <br /><br />I called you a 'penniless pothead'.  You're the one who described himself as one who might 'spend the next 36 hours smokin dope and watching movies'...so 'pothead' is just descriptive.<br /><br />And since when is it an insult to be 'penniless'? I've been poor myself.  Its nothing to be ashamed of in and of itself.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I can't help but thinking to myself that I sure hope for their sake that you researched your clients cases better than you researched your "legal advice" in response to this thread<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />More whiny crap.<br /><br />Look...believe it or not, Drex, I really am trying to do YOU, and anyone else as gullible as you who reads this thread a favor.  <br /><br />The basic problem with the 'opt out' arguments is that they take a few lines of text from a few cases widely separated in time and circumstances, and then ignore the hundreds of concrete cases that specifically disagree with them.  They then go on to ignore the actual holdings and results in the cases they cite. 'Taking things out of context' is totally inadequate to describe the process.  Its junk, not legal argument.<br /><br />Almost everyone who buys into this 'opt out' nonsense winds up in serious legal and financial trouble.  The exceptions are invariably people so poor they wouldn't pay income taxes anyway, and people who deal only in cash.  Its common for people to get away with fudging their taxes once in a while....or even with skipping a year.  Sometimes people get lucky.  IRS employees ARE civil servants, and they miss a lot.  <br /><br />But people who stop filing and stop paying taxes, year after year, inevitably get noticed if anyone is paying them by check, and then the IRS and the Justice Department come down on them like a ton of bricks.  They bury them under a mountain of penalties it can take them decades to climb over.  It's sad.<br /><br />I've known people who got mixed up in this sort of stupidity.  Most of them weren't bad people.  Some of them weren't even unpleasant people.  They were just gullible, the kind of people who believe that if something _sounds_ reasonable, its true.<br /><br />Its my hope that by dredging up the unpleasant facts that show these 'opt out' arguments are B.S., some poor gullible schlep is saved from making a ruin of his life.  Maybe that schlep will even be you.  Although it doesn't sound like you have much in the way of income taxes to worry about now, things change.<br /><br />Why do I care?  I dunno.  I did business fraud litigation for several years after getting my J.D..  Most of my clients were gullible people, or the people who took advantage of them.  I quit because it was REALLY depressing.  I always thought most of my clients (or their adversaries) could have avoided a courtroom if somebody a little more knowledgeable had pointed out a couple things to them ahead of time.  <br /><br />Bah...its probably wishful thinking.  Most of my experience both in law and out has indicated gullible people are more likely to believe a pleasant lie than an unpleasant truth...at least until the truth creeps up on them and tears out a chunk of flesh. <br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
