                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"> gibberish form letter <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />99 people out of 100 who send a letter like this to the IRS will get their tax records flagged for audit and enforcement.  If they have actually failed to file a return, or filed a fraudulent return, they will typically get hit for 10s of thousands of dollars in civil penalties, and have their wages garnished and their property seized and encumbered by leins.<br /><br />If they are obstinate and refuse to acknowledge their tax liabilities, the IRS will refer their matter for criminal prosecution to the Justice Department.<br /><br />At that point, most people are facing the prospect of a criminal trial which can put them in prison for several years, and don't have the 10s of thousands of dollars needed money to pay a private attorney.  Most give in and plea bargain.  The government wants them to pay up, not go to prison, and offers terms that are generous by the standards of most criminal prosecutions.  But some people are 'lucky' enough to find attorneys who will represent them and remain in denial.<br /><br />A bit more 2 out of 3 of those people wind up serving prison sentences of 1-5 years, depending on how extensive their tax evasion has been.  It can be tough to prove that a scofflaw's failure to understand his obligations is insincere, but the Justice Department manages most of the time.<br /><br />So some people avoid going to prison, but they are still perma-broke at the end of the process.  And if they continue to refuse to file and pay, the government WILL bring criminal charges again.<br /><br />It boils down to this:  The fact that SOME people beat a criminal charge at a jury trial doesn't mean the crime for which they were prosecuted does not exist.  For example, O.J. Simpson beat a murder charge.  It doesn't follow that murder is not a crime.<br /><br />Anyway, I've seen what happens to people who do as Drexyll advocates.  Its not pretty.  Even the people Drexyll gives as examples of people who 'win' wind up broke and worse off than if they had just payed their taxes in the first place.  And most people who 'opt out' are not even THAT lucky.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I gave you one free piece of advice, now you want more? Forget it. Go hire a malpractice attorney.<br />-----------------------------------------------<br />LMAO Made ya a little nervous with that one?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Not exactly.  <br /><br />There is _zero_ danger I'm going to lose a malpractice case as a result of  discouraging people from breaking the tax laws and then telling the IRS about it...which is what the 'opt out' movement advocates.<br /><br />But I cannot remember all the elements of malpractice, and am not enthusiastic enough about arguing with you to go dig out my torts outline.  Its in storage down in the sub-basement.  And its kind of icky down there.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
