eight="1" noshade id="quote"><br />At that point, most people are facing the prospect of a criminal trial which can put them in prison for several years, and don't have the 10s of thousands of dollars needed money to pay a private attorney.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Speaking of criminal trials, did I mention that link I posted about the one this past month where the person was acquitted?  As for not having the money to pay a private attorney, I'd say that's because most folks have been mislead by "the lawyers cabal" into thinking such is the case, and are unaware of Libertarian Party tax attorneys in all 50 states that typically take on these cases for free.  Sorry, I know you "regular lawyers" don't like ppl to talk about "those kinds of lawyers" <img src="images/jester_125.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" /><br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />Most give in and plea bargain.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Fools that don't know any better.  Most do it do to poor legal advice, IMO.<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />But some people are 'lucky' enough to find attorneys who will represent them and remain in denial.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />If anyone feels like getting lucky, send me a PM with the state you live in and I'll get you a list of LP tx attorneys that will work for free or for whatever you can afford.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />A bit more 2 out of 3 of those people wind up serving prison sentences of 1-5 years, depending on how extensive their tax evasion has been.  It can be tough to prove that a scofflaw's failure to un