h - OJ ain't in jail, is he?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />Anyway, I've seen what happens to people who do as Drexyll advocates.  Its not pretty.  Even the people Drexyll gives as examples of people who 'win' wind up broke and worse off than if they had just payed their taxes in the first place.  And most people who 'opt out' are not even THAT lucky.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That's not true.  Gimme a day or two (I really am going out to do some work here in a little bit, LOL) to post some success stories.  You're looking at ppl that you've seen "get lucky" at a jury trial.  What about ppl that declare sovereign citizenship, for example?  They're never bothered again.  Sure, they cant vote, have to get an international drivers liccense, etc etc, but they dont get bothered by the IRS anymore, and they don't EVER get charged for it once the process is complete, do they?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I gave you one free piece of advice, now you want more? Forget it. Go hire a malpractice attorney.<br />-----------------------------------------------<br />LMAO Made ya a little nervous with that one?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Not exactly.  <br /><br />There is _zero_ danger I'm going to lose a malpractice case as a result of  discouraging people from breaking the tax laws and then telling the IRS about it...which is what the 'opt out' movement advocates.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I honestly wasn't imlpying a malpractice case, I was just curious as to the technical legalities of dispensing "legal advice."<br /><br /><