                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> The revolution is over, Mr. Lebowski!  The bums lost!<br /><br />Anyway, to address the original post:<br /><br />I actually own a hospital.  Not a big one, mind you, but a hospital none-the-less.  I don't mind people like Drex coming in for care one bit because he actually intended to pay- but he is an anomoly.  Most of the time private pay (which is what he would be classified as) means no pay.  If a person doesn't have private insurance or doesn't qualify for medicare or medicaid (tencare in his situation) that means we are going to be fucked.  Most hospitals don't get paid by the care programs what it actually costs to provide services, they get a percentage, and as a result the private pay and insurance payee's make up the difference.  I'm greatly simplifying, but there you go.  Everything we do is regulated.  I'm not at all surprised a health clinic wouldn't take you without some form of id.<br /><br />Also, it costs a fortune to run an ER.  I don't know who upthread said most ER's are run by teaching hospitals- but that isn't the case.  In fact, in the hundred or so hospitals I've been in over the last four years or so, I haven't run into one where this was the situation.<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
